<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,334,675,701]" box="[189,334,675,701]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,675,701]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,675,701]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,659,721,748]" box="[189,659,721,748]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
SIZE. Habitus length 
<quantity box="[431,536,722,748]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.4" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="0.74">0.74 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[551,646,721,748]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1398,787,848]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">COLOUR. Dark brown/black, shining, appearing polished, glabrous, legs and antennae yellow/brown, antennal club darker.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,887,1055]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
HEAD. With distinctive sculpturing behind eye, including a single linear depression extending across vertex (
<figureCitation box="[281,372,923,949]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
) and much larger and deeper depression with pair of setae behind eyes; width across eyes 
<quantity box="[247,353,958,984]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.20 mm</quantity>
; antennomeres III–XI length 
<quantity box="[693,799,958,984]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="0.26">0.26 mm</quantity>
, X–XI forming a distinct club; mentum front angles rounded, then tapering slightly to wide base, prementum wide from side to side but narrow from front to back, with four setae.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" startId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" targetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,1965,2027]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,268,1965,1991]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Darby, 2020" authorityName="Darby" authorityYear="2020" box="[278,623,1965,1991]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Discheramocephalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[278,623,1965,1991]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Discheramocephalus striatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[632,725,1966,1992]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[734,755,1965,1991]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">A</emphasis>
. Habitus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[879,899,1965,1991]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">B</emphasis>
. Pronotum ×570. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1118,1139,1965,1991]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">C</emphasis>
. Side of head ×1520. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,210,2001,2027]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">D</emphasis>
. Meso- and metaventra ×460. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[570,590,2001,2027]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">E</emphasis>
. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,267,438]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
PRONOTUM. Length 
<quantity box="[431,548,267,294]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.16">0.16 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[650,766,267,294]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.22">0.22 mm</quantity>
, sparsely pubescent, with two longitudinal, linear depressions situated medially and two at sides, medial depressions widest basally and flanked by pair of much shorter foveae on each side, outermost ones slightly longer than innermost pair, pronotal lateral margins strongly sinuate posteriorly, widening to posterior angles, lateral margin with two distinct, setae-bearing concave insinuations in front of scutellum (
<figureCitation box="[862,954,412,438]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1398,478,540]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
ELYTRA. Length 
<quantity box="[376,483,478,505]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.51">0.51 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[566,673,478,504]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.33">0.33 mm</quantity>
, finely striate throughout, sparsely pubescent, evenly rounded, sutural margins strongly bordered (
<figureCitation box="[601,693,514,540]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 8E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1395,580,607]" box="[189,1395,580,607]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">SCUTELLUM. Triangular, with narrow median keel broadest at base and extending to sharp point at apex.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1398,647,781]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
MESOVENTRITE. Collar broad, strongly reticulate, sharply angled posteriad at anterior angles, forming two deep pits and barely extending onto humeri, which are without teeth, without mid-keel, medial, raised extension of collar joining with anterior margin of metaventrite; mesepiventral suture from middle of collar extension to outside of mesocoxae clearly marked (
<figureCitation box="[866,960,755,781]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,821,992]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
METAVENTRITE. Length 
<quantity box="[465,575,821,848]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.19">0.19 mm</quantity>
(measured to anterior tip of extension between mesocoxae), width 
<quantity box="[189,300,857,884]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.26">0.26 mm</quantity>
, sparsely pubescent, with wide anterior extension between mesocoxae terminating in blunt point, lateral margins running into mesocoxal cavity borders, marked by two long setae; positions of metepiventral sutures visible as extensions of those on mesoventrite, effaced before reaching posterior margin of metaventrite (
<figureCitation box="[473,568,965,992]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,615,1032,1058]" box="[189,615,1032,1058]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
MALE GENITALIA. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[515,601,1032,1058]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,1102,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[186,1401,1096,1927]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. Discheramocephalus striatus sp. nov. A. Habitus. B. Pronotum ×570. C. Side of head ×1520. D. Meso- and metaventra ×460. E. Elytra showing striations and sutural margin ×1120." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3659596" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3659596/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig 8B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,546,1098,1125]" box="[189,546,1098,1125]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">FEMALE GENITALIA. Not known.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,303,1165,1191]" box="[189,303,1165,1191]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1165,1191]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1165,1191]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,1212,1310]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
The description of this species based on a single specimen is justified because only one other specimen of the genus is known from the country (see preceding species). It is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Darby, 2020" authorityName="Darby" authorityYear="2020" box="[1233,1399,1249,1274]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Discheramocephalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigerrimus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1233,1399,1249,1274]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">D. nigerrimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[189,280,1284,1310]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and all other known 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2007" box="[528,776,1284,1310]" class="Insecta" family="Ptiliidae" genus="Discheramocephalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[528,776,1284,1310]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Discheramocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. by the presence of the striae on the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
